[Classically, botulism is a foodborne disease caused by the ingestion of preformed toxin, although there also exists wound botulism (in which _Clostridium botulinum_ spores germinate in a wound), and infant botulism (in which the spores germinate in the intestinal tract).

Types A, B, and E of human botulism are the commonest. Type E is often associated with food from marine sources. Although all types have a similar symptom complex, Hughes and colleagues report that type E is much more likely to produce initial lethargic mental status and more autonomic dysfunction (1). Many of the cases are type E related to the ingestion of salted or dried fish (2).

References
----------
1. Hughes JM, Hatheway CL, Ostroff SM: Botulism. In: Scheld WM, Whitley RJ, Durack DT, editors. Infections of the central nervous system. 2nd edition. Philadelphia: Lippincott-Raven, 1997, 615-28.
2. Weber JT, Hibbs RG, Darwish A, et al. A massive outbreak of type E botulism associated with traditional salted fish in Cairo. J Infect Dis. 1993; 167(2): 451-4. Abstract available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8421179.

The North Island, also officially named Te Ika-a-Maui, (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Island) is one of the 2 main islands of New Zealand, separated from the larger but much less populous South Island by Cook Strait. The island's area is 113729 square km (43,911 sq mi), making it the world's 14th-largest island. It has a population of 3 760 900 (June 2019). - Mod.LL]
